### Correlation.  

Find the multicollinearity in the independent variables.  
using rcorr from Hmisc package, calculate correlation matrix. Filter out any insignificant P <0.01 correlations.

```{r corr_1}
rcorr_matrix <- residential_clean_df %>%
  select(-OBJECTID, -PRICE, -QUALIFIED) %>%
  rcorr()
corrplot(rcorr_matrix$r, type='upper', order = 'hclust',tl.cex = 0.6,tl.srt = 70)
```
  
  
```{r corr_2}
corrplot(rcorr_matrix$r, type='upper', order = 'hclust',tl.cex = 0.6,tl.srt = 70,
         p.mat = rcorr_matrix$P, sig.level = 0.01, insig = 'pch', pch = '*')

```
  
Structure and landarea_bucket have very strong -ve correlation.  
Landuse, num_units and kitchens have strong +ve correlation.  
bathroom_total, gba_bucket and rooms have strong +ve correlations.  
plot the correlogram of these variables with PRICE.  
```{r corr_3}
rcor_price <- residential_clean_df %>%
  filter(QUALIFIED == 'Q', !is.na(PRICE)) %>%
  select(PRICE, STRUCT, LANDAREA_Bucket, LAND_USE, KITCHENS, NUM_UNITS,ROOMS, BATHROOM_TOTAL,GBA_Bucket) %>%
  as.matrix() %>%
  rcorr()
corrplot(rcor_price$r, type='upper', order = 'hclust',tl.cex = 0.6,tl.srt = 70,
         p.mat = rcor_price$P, sig.level = 0.01, insig = 'pch', pch = '*')
```  
Selecting BATHROOM_TOTAL, ROOMS, GBA_BUCKET and STRUCT. others will be dropped.
